text.tspan: TRANSFERS POWER FROM TRUNK TO DRAGON
CONTAINS SENSORS THAT TRACK THE ISS DURING APPROACH
THE ISS CANADARM GRAPPLES HERE TO BERTH AND UNBERTH DRAGON 1
PROTECTS BERTHING PORT DURING ATMOSPHERIC FLIGHT
SUPPORTS AND PROTECTS SOLAR ARRAYS DURING LAUNCH
GENERATES UP TO 5 KILOWATTS OF ELECTRICITY
WHILE THE FALCON 9 WILL BE HUMAN-RATED IN TIME
FOR CARRYING DRAGON 2, DRAGON 1 IS NOT HUMAN-RATED
AND ONLY CARRIES CARGO TO THE ISS. IN THE NEAR FUTURE,
DRAGON 2 WILL REPLACE DRAGON 1 FOR BOTH CARGO AND CREW.
THE DRAGON 1 CAPSULE DOES NOT HAVE LAUNCH ABORT CAPABILITY, AS A CARGO CAPSULE DOES NOT
REQUIRE THIS FUNCTIONALITY. FUTURE CARGO FLIGHTS, PERFORMED ON THE DRAGON 2, WILL HAVE LAUNCH
THE DRAGON 1 CAPSULE IS BERTHED TO THE ISS, WHEREAS THE DRAGON 2 CAPSULE DOCKS AUTONOMOUSLY.
BERTHING IS MANUALLY PERFORMED WITH THE ISS CANADARM, AND DOCKING IS FULLY AUTONOMOUS AND
REQUIRES NO HUMAN INPUT. HOWEVER, THE DOCKING PORT IS SMALLER THAN THE BERTHING PORT, WHICH
MAKES BERTHING MORE SUITED TO CARGO.
COMMON BERTHING MECHANISM CONNECTS DRAGON TO ISS
USED TO LOAD AND UNLOAD CARGO ON EARTH
THE NOSECONE IS JETTISONED SHORTLY AFTER
THE FALCON 9 IGNITES ITS SECOND STAGE ENGINE.
